        "identifier": "B",
        "content": " -COOH\n"
      },
      {
        "identifier": "C",
        "content": " $-\\mathrm{C}_2 \\mathrm{H}_5$\n"
      },
      {
        "identifier": "D",
        "content": " $-\\mathrm{NO}_2$"
      }
    ],
    "correct_options": [
      "C"
    ],
    "answer": null,
    "explanation": "<p>Inductive effect is the electron-pushing or –pulling ability of a substituent through σ-bonds. A “+I” group donates electrons toward the rest of the molecule, while a “–I” group withdraws electrons.</p>\n<p>Step-by-step analysis of each option:</p>\n\n<p><p>–COOR (ester)  </p>\n<p>• Oxygen is quite electronegative, so the –COOR group pulls electron density through σ-bonds.  </p>\n<p>• This is a –I effect.</p></p>\n<p><p>–COOH (carboxyl)  </p>\n<p>• Both the carbonyl C=O and the –OH oxygen withdraw electron density.  </p>\n<p>• Net effect is strongly –I.</p></p>\n<p><p>–C₂H₅ (ethyl)  </p>\n<p>• An alkyl group is less electronegative than hydrogen and tends to push electron density toward the rest of the molecule.  </p>\n<p>• This is a +I effect.</p></p>\n<p><p>–NO₂ (nitro)  </p>\n<p>• The nitro group is a strong electron-withdrawing group through both induction and resonance.  </p>\n<p>• This is a –I effect.</p></p>\n\n<p>Answer: The only group that exhibits a +I effect is  </p>\n<p>$$-\\mathrm{C}_2\\mathrm{H}_5\\,. $$</p>",
